AT APPROX. 1800 HRS DEC. 12,1992, A CONRAIL TRAIN CREW WAS IN THE PROCESS OF SERVICING REILLY TAR & CHEMICAL WITH TANK CARS FOR THEIR UNLOADING RACK WHEN THEY WERE ASKED BY REILLY TAR & CHEMICAL TO MOVE ONE OF THEIR STORAGE TANK CARS FROM ONE TRACK TO ANOTHER. UPON MOVING THE TANK CAR, PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR ONTO THE GROUND AND SIDES OF THE TANK CAR.  AN INSPECTION FO THE TANK INDICATED THE MANWAY WAS CLOSED, BUT NOT SECURED, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPRAY OUT. THE CONRAIL TRAINMASTER, J.A. HARPER, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND NOTICED THE TANK HAD FOUR CORROSIVE PLACARDS.  HE WAS ADVISED BY REILLY TAR & CHEMICAL THAT THE PRODUCT NAME WAS "PLOY ALKY PYRIDINES".  REILLY TAR & CHEMICAL AND SPARKS CONTRUCTION SECURED THE MANWAY AND PERFORMED THE NECESSARY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP.

column168: ON 12/26/92 A RUPTURE DISC BLEW ON BENZOIC ACID CAR NATX 28054 DURING THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL FROM THIS CAR TO ANOTHER VESSEL.  THE CAR WAS PRESSURED WITH REGULATED NITROGEN SUPPLY @ 40 PSIG.  AT THE TIME OF THIS TRANSFER ONLY 8665 GALLONS OF BENZIOC ACID WAS IN THE CAR.  THE RELEASE PRODUCED A CLOUD OF NITROGEN SATURATED WITH BENZOIC ACID. WHEN THE RELEASE OCCURRED THE NITROGEN SUPPLY TO THE CAR WAS CLOSED, A FIRE MONITOR WAS USED TO APPLY A WATER SPRAY TO CONTAIN ANY VAPOR CLOUD, AND AS SOON AS THE CAR DEPRESSURIZED THE RELEASE WAS TERMINATED. AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A 45 PSIG. RUPTURE DISC HAD BEEN INSTALLED BY THE RAILCAR COMPANY INSTEAD OF THE REQUIRED 60 PSIG DISC. THIS CAR WAS ONE OF TEN NEW CARS TO ENTER THE COMPANY'S FLEET OF CARS FOR BENZOIC ACID SERVICE.  ALL OF THESE NEW CARS ARE BEING INSPECTED TO CHECK RUPTURE DISC RATING, AND ARE BEGING CHANGED.

WHILE UNHOOKING #2 FUEL OIL LOADING ARM FROM CARGO TANK AT KERR-MCGEE LOADING TERMINAL IN MCFARLAND, WI THE LOADER LOST CONTROL OF THE ARM.  THE ARM SWUNG TOWARDS THE LOADING PIPE AND BROKE A VALVE USED TO RETRIEVE SAMPLES OF PRODUCT OFF THE PIPING.  THIS CAUSED PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED FROM THE LOADING PIPE INTO THE LOADING BAY AREA. THE LOADER WAS NOT AWARE OF A SHUT OFF VALVE DIRECTLY AT THE BOTTOM OF THE PIPE.  HE THEN PUSHED THE FIRE ALARM SYSTEM WHICH CAUSED WATER AND FOAM TO FLOOD THE LOADING AREA.BECAUSE OF THE LARGE AMOUNT OF WATER AND FOAM WHICH FLOODED THE AREA A LARGE AMOUNT OF FUEL OIL FLOWED DOWN THE DRIVEWAY AND ONTO THE KERR-MCGEE PROPERTY AND ALSO UNDER A FENCE INTO A FIELD ADJACENT TO THE PROPERTY. TERMIANL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY TO SHUT FIRE SYSTEM DOWN AND REPAIR VALVE.  DOLLAR AMOUNTS OF LOSS ARE UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME.  PROPERTY DAMAGE AND CLEANUP COSTS ARE PENDING DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS.

column168: DRIVER HAD ARRIVED FROM LITTLE ROCK, AR. AND PARKED THE UNIT IN THE YARD TEMPORARILY.  AFTER A FEW MINUTES DRIVER WENT OUT TO MOVE UNIT WHEN HE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR NEAR THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE SUPERVISOR AND DETERMINED THE CAUSE.  THE FIRE DEPT. WAS CALLED AND AFTER ARRIVING THEY SUGGESTED THAT A EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY BE CALLED. FERGUSON HARBOUR ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT METAL FATIGUE WAS THE CAUSE.  A SECTION OF THE FLOOR WAS LATER TAKEN OUT AND WILL BE DISPOSED ALONG WITH THE WASTE THAT WAS ACCUMALTED.  SHIPPER ACCEPTS ALL RESPONSIBLITIES AND COST PERTAINING TO THIS INCIDENT.  THE REMAINING THREE PAILS WERE ALSO PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM IN THE EVENT THAT THEY MAY BEGIN TO LEAK.  (A MOBAY CHEMICAL PRODUCT).

column168: ON WEDNESDAY DECEMBER 9, 1992, DAVID AUTRY, A WEST BROTHERS DRIVER WAS MAKING ADELIVERY AT THE DURHAM HERALD SUN. BECAUSE HE HAD A ROLL DOOR TRAILER, HEBACKED UP TO THE DOCK AND WENT IN THE BUILDING TO PREPARE TO UNLOAD. WHEN HEROLLED UP THE DOOR ON THE TRAILER, HE NOTICED THAT THE FLOOR WAS WET AND ASTRONG ODOR WAS BEING EMITTED FROM THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE DOORTO THE TRAILER. HE WAITED A FEW MINUTES AND ONCE AGAIN TO VIEW THE INSIDE OFTHE TRAILER, BUT WAS UNABLE TO BECAUSE OF THE ODOR. FROM LOOKING AT THE FREIGHTBILLS, HE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT HE WAS HAULING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HECALLED THE DISPATCHER WHO TOLD HIM TO GO TO THE DURHAM TERMINAL SINCE HE WAS SOCLOSE TO THIS LOCATION. AFTER ARRIVING AT THE DURHAM TERMINAL, HE PARKED THETRAILER. HE CONSULTED RON MILLS, DIRECTOR OF MAINTENANCE, WHO THEN CALLEDCHEMTREC TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE PROBLEM. THE DURHAM COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT ANDHAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WERE ALERTED TO THE PROBLEM. THEY ARRIVED A SHORT TIMELATER AND BEGAN THE PROCESS OF DETERMINING THE AMOUNT AND EXTENT OF THE SPILL.THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM DETERMINED AT THE COMPLETION OFTHE THEIR WORK THAT A CORRUGATED CARD BOARD BOX HELD THE LIQUID THAT LEAKED.INSIDE THE BOX WAS A POLYURETHENE BLADDER WHICH CONTAINED 5 1/4 GALLONS OF 360FIXER PART A AND A QUART BOTTLE OF ACETIC ACID. THE FINDINGS OF THE HAZARDOUSMATERIALS TEAM WAS THAT THE BLADDER CONTAINING THE FIXER WAS LEAKING.ENVIRO-CHEM, INC. WAS CONTACTED CONCERNING THE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSITION OF THEITEMS THAT WERE IN THE BOX, INCLUDING THE BOX. MR. TRACY CLARK INDICATED THATTHE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER COULD BE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUMCOARBONATE. ENVIRO-CHEM DISPOSED OF THE BLADDER AND PUT THE REMAINING LIQUIDINTO THREE GLASS JARS. THE BOTTLE  OF ACETIC ACID WERE GIVEN TO MR. RICHARDESTERLING, A REPRESENTATIVE OF ANITEC, THE COMPANY WHICH SHIPPED THE FRIGHT.THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT THAT WAS ON THE TRAILER WAS DELIVERED WITH THEEXCEPTION OF ONE CARTON OF THE ACETIC ACID SOLUTION AND 1 BOX OF PHOTOGRAPHERSMATERIAL FAX 70, THESE WERE BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE CAUSE OF THESPILL HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED. A MR. ROGER SCHUMER, AND ENVIRONMENT ENGINEER,WITH ANITEC INDICATED DURING A PHONE CONVERSATION THAT THERE HAD BEEN PROBLEMSWITH THE CAP ON THE BLADDER AND SAID THAT THERE HAD BEEN LEAKAGE IN THE PASTAROUND THE CAP. MR. EASTERLING INDICATED THAT THE BLADDER WOULD NOT LEAK,UNLESS THE ITEM WAS DROPPED. THERE WAS NO INDICATION FROM THE CONDITION OF THEBOX THAT IT HAD BEEN DROPPED. THE CAP TO THE  BLADDER WAS DISCOVERED BY MR.EASTERLING AND WAS BROKEN. THERE IS NO WAY TO DETERMINE IF THE CAP WAS BROKENWHILE STILL ON THE BLADDER OR IF IT WAS STEPPED ON BY THE HAZ MAT TEAM OR MR.CLARK FROM ENVIRO-CHEM.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.(UST). THIS CAUSED ABOUT 10 GALLONS OF GAS TO SPILL ONTO THE BLACKTOP.  THE GAS WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH PADS AND CLAY ABSORBANTS.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WASNOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9211113 TO THIS INCIDENT.  THE UST'S OVERFILL PROTECTION VALVE IS MANUFACTURED BY OPW FUELING COMPONENTS GROUP OF CINCINNATI, OHIO.  MODEL #OPW61-SO. CERTIFIED #P026532309

column168: THIS WAS A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK AT A CONVENIECE STORE.  IT WAS VERY COLD AND SNOWING HEAVILY WHEN OUR DRIVR ARRIVED.  THE ABOVE GROUND TANK IS EQUIPPED WITH A TAPE GAUGE TO MEASURE THE CONTENTS.  AS FAR AS WE CAN TELL, THE TAPE GAUGE MUST HAVE BEEN FROZEN OR STUCK WHEN OUR DRIVER TOOK HIS INITIAL READINGS.  USING THE INITIAL READING, THEPRODUCT SHOULD HAVE FIT INT HE TANK WITH NO PROBLEMS.  BUT AS THE DRIVER WAS NEARING THE END OF HIS DELIVERY, THE GAS BLEW OUT OF THE TANKS TOP VENT AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE IMPERVIOUS DYKING AROUND IT.  THE NEEW YORK STATE DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9210471 TO THE INCIDENT.  SPILL CLEANED UP BY OP-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL OF MASEENA, NEW YORK.

column168: ON DECEMBER 2, 1992 CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT UNIT #25 WAS TRAVELING NORTH IN THE RIGHT LANE ON U S HIGHWAY 90 IN MORGAN CTIY, LOUISANA.  AS OUR DRIVER, DON HICKS, SLOWED FOR A TRAFFIC LIGHT, A PICK-UP TRUCK FOLLOWING OUR UNIT APPARENTLY COULD NOT STOP.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PASS O UR UNIT TO THE LEFT AND SIDE-SWPIED ANOTHER PICK U P WHICH WAS TRAVELING IN THE SAME DIRECTION.  THIS KNOCKED THE OTHER VEHICLE UNDER OUR TRAILER.  THE DRIVER OF THE FIRST PICK-UP WAS ISSUED A CITATION. AS A RESULT OF THE SUDDEN BRAKING, SEVERAL DRUMS SHIFTED FORWARD CAUSING FOUR DRUMS TO BE PUNCTURED BY THE RING LID BOLT. OUR DRY VAN TRAILERS HAVE A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN TO CONTAIN ANY LEAKAGE IN THE TRAILER.  THIS PAN WAS DAMAGED BY THE FORCE OF TE DRUMS SHIFTING FORWARD AND WAS NOT TOTAL EFFECTIVE IN ITS PURPOSE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DIKED AND ABSORBED WITH DIRT AND REMOVED FOR THE HIGHWAY AND PLACED IN THE TRAILER. FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ASSISTED OUR DRIVER IN CONTAINING AND REMOVING THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE FIRE CHIEF THEN ALLOWED OUR TRUCK TO BE MOVED ABOUT A MILE AWAY TO MARINE SHALE PROCESSORS FACILITY IN ORDER THAT THE ENTIRE LOAD BE INSPECTED AND THE DAMAGED DRUMS BE OVERPACKED THEN RELOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER. SINCE THERE WAS DAMAGE TO OUR TRAILER AND OUR PARENT COMPANY HAD EMPTY TRAILERS NEARBY, I ARRANGED FOR A VAN TO REPLACE THE DAMAGED VAN IN ORDER THAT THE SHIPMENT COULD BE DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE DAMAGED VAN WAS TRANSPORTED TO OUR FACILITY IN HAMPTON, AR A FEW DAYS LATER AND REPAIRED. ONE OF THE INVOLVED VEHICLES CALLED THE MORAGAN CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE TO THE SCENE VIA A CELLUAR PHONE. I AN INVESTIGATING THE AVAILABLE OPTIONS THAT MAY OFFER INCREASED LOAD SECURITY FOR DRUM TRANSPORTATION.  I HAVE IMPLEMENTED POLICY THAT ALL VAN TRAILERS CARRY AT LEAST FOUR LOAD LOCKS AND THAT AT LEAST TWO E-LOCK BARS BE USED TO PREVENT THE FORWARD MOVEMENT IN EMERGENCY STOPS.

OUR LOADER DON MEDDINGS IN AN EFFORT TO ASSIST THE SHIPPER AND DRIVER TO OVERCOME A VALVE PROBLEM ON MATLACK TR#6087 WHICH WAS UNFORSEEN, USED BAD JUDGEMENT WHEN REMOVING A SPECIAL STEAM FITTING WHICH WAS USED WHEN NORMAL STEAMING WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. column168: ON DECEMBER 9, 1992 AT 11:40 A.M.  DISPATCHER ANN STONE RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. JEFF MEYERS OF THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. MR. MEYERS REPORTED A SPILL FROM ONE OF OUR TANKERS AT OAKDALE LA ON U S HIGHWAY 165.  HE ALSO STATED THERE WAS ANOTHER AREA OF SPILLAGE AT THE INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 165 AND INTERSTATE 10. THE ALLEN PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE WAS CONTACTED TO CONFIRM SPILL AND DETERMINE EXACT LOCATION OF TRACTOR/TRAILER. A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. O.H. MATERIALS, PORT ALLEN, LA. AND CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, HOUSTON TX. WERE CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. THE SPILL APPEARS TO HAVE OCCURRED AT FOUR INTERSECTIONS.  FIRST, AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY. 165 AND I 10.  SECOND ON HWY. 165 KINDER, LA THIRD ON HWY 165 IN OBERLIN LA. FINALLY, ON HWY 165 SOUTH OF OAKDALE LA EACH LOCATION WAS DECONTAMINATED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QWUALITY.  ALL WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE TO ENSCO, INC., AMERICAN OIL ROAD, EL DORADO, AR.  THERE WERE 54 DRUMS OF MATERIAL AND 200 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED WATER SENT TO THIS FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. IT HAD BEEN DETERMINED BY FULL INVESTIGATION, THE LEAK WAS CAUSED  BY AN UNSECURED MANHOLE.  THE DRIVER HAD BEEN DISCIPLINED FOR NOT FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURES WHEN LOADING TANK TRAILER.  (PROCEDURES ATTACHED) THE DRIVER WAS A 15 YEAR VETERAM WITH A CLEAN RECORD.  THERE ARE NO OTHER INCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS IN HIS RECORD. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE RADIUS SURROUNDING THE TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS. ALSO DURING THIS TIME VEHICLES WERE DETOUED AROUND THIS SECTOR OF HIGHWAY 165. DUE TO THE OFFENSIVE ODOR OF THE MATERIAL, 15 PEOPLE REPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF NAUSEA. ONE ELDERLY GENTLEMAN HYPERVENTILATED DURING THE EVACUATION PROCESS AND WAS KEPT IN THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ORIGINALLY MANIFESTED AS A NON REGULATED HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID. column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED THAT MP 14564 WAS LEAKING DIESEL FUEL. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE GATE VALVE HAD BEEN LEFT ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET DURING TRANSIT. DUE TO THE EXTREME COLD WEATHER, THE FUEL HAD FROZEN AND RUPTURED THE VALVE WHICH ALLOWED LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT. THE BROKEN VALVE WAS REMOVED AND REPLACE, BOTTOM OUTLET PLUG INSERTED AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP SECURED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. ABSORBENT PADS AND FLOOR DRY WERE FOR USED CLEANUP. THE FROZEN GROUND CONDITIONS TO BE RECOVERED AND SENT TO THE SEPARATION PLANT IN POCATELLO, ID. NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO THE NATIONAL SPILL CONTROL CENTER AND IDAHO DIVISION OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.

column168: NEVADA HWY PATROL REPORT 1292-P-119-RS03. ON DECEMBER 11, 1992, I REPORTED TOWORK AT BERRY-HINCKLEY TERMINAL INC. I STATRTED UNIT #29 AND DID A REGULAR DOTPRE-TRIP NOTICING NO DEFECTS OR APPARENT PROBLEMS OF ANY KIND. I LEFT AT 4:00AMAND NOTICED SANDING AT PYRAMID AND INTERSTATE 80 BUT NONE ON 395 SOUTH TOWARDCARSON CITY. I DROPPED DOWN OFF OF 395 TO SURFACE ROAD WAY AND NOTICED THE ROADWAS SPARKLING AND LOOKED WET. I NOTICED NO APPARENT DRIVING PROBLEM AT THATTIME. I PROCEEDED SLOWLY TOWARDS CARSON CITY, AFTER APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE, ISAW THE LIGHT AT SOUTH HILLS DRIVE HAD CHANGED TO RED. I KNEW I HAD TO SLOW ORCOME TO A STOP. I TAPPED THE BRAKE AND LET UP AND FELT THE UNIT MOVING ACROSSTHE LAST LANE. I STAYED IN CONTROL FOR A FEW SECONDS, SEEMINGLY, AND THOUGHT ICOULD RECOVER CONTROL. AT THE CENTER LINE, I KNEW IT WAS A LOST CAUSE. I TRIEDTO KEEP FROM LEAVING THE ROAD WAY. I FELT THAT THE TRUCK SPIN HAD STOPPED ANDLOOKED IN MY SIDE REAR VIEW MIRROR. I SAW FLAMES SHOOTING UPWARD FROM THETRAILER (29A). I JUMPED CLEAR AND RAN FOR SAFETY. THE WASHOE COUNTY SHERIFF WASON SCENE ALMOST IMMEDIATELY. I WAVED TO HIM AND ANSWERED HIS QUESTIONS AT THETIME. WE STOPPED FRAFFIC HE CALLED APPROPIATE AUTHORITIES. HE THEN CALLEDLAWRENCE WAUGH TERMINAL MANAGER FOR BERRY-HINCKLEY TERMINAL. I HEARD NO SOUNDSOF ANY KIND, BUT SAW ONLY THE FLAMES OF THE TRAILER FIRE. I RAN FOR SAFETY ANDHELP.

column168: CF1 DRIVER DAN HOLMES DISCOVERED A POSSIBLE LEAK WHILE TRAVELING NORTH ON HWY 77 IN ROUTE TO HOUSTON, TX.  HE PULLED OFF THE HWY INTO A ROADSIDE PARK TO INVESTIGATE THE PROBELM.  DAN THEN EVACUATED THE PEOPLE IN THE AREA AND SENT MR. JAMES CLAY A CFL DRIVER TO CALL HIS DISPATCHER.  THE DISPATCHER THEN CONTACTED TONY CONWAY CFL SAFETY MGR WHO THEN CONTACTED CHEMTREC.  THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES THEN COTACTED TONY AND THE SHIPPER ON WHAT PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW.  THE MANUFACTURERE DISPATCHED HIS REPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE WHILE TONY CONWAY SENT THE CFL RESPONSE TEAM TO THE LOCATION. THE UNICHEM REP ARRIVED AT THE SITE AT APPROX. 2:00 A.M. THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVE DID NOT HAVE THE SECONDARY CAP IN PLACE THEREFORE, THE VALVE VIBRATED OPEN AND CAUSED THE LEAK.  THE VALVE WAS SHUT OFF AND THE CLEANUP PROCESS STARTED.  THE CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED UDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE DOT AND THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION.  THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED BY 10:30 AM AND MET THE APPROVAL OF BOTH THE DOT AND THE TWC.  THE MATERIALS USED FOR THE CLEANUP ARE NOW WAITING TO BE DISPOSED OF AT A SUITABLE LOCATION.

AS VERBALLY REPORTED TO THE NRC ON DECEMBER 11, 1992, A HAZARDOUS GAS WASRELEASED AT THE ABOVE REFERENCED DOWELL SCHLUMBERGER INCORPORATED (DSI)FACILITY ON DECEMBER 11, 1992. THE PURPOSE OF THIS LETTER IS TO SERVE ASWRITTEN NOTIFICATION OF THE RELEASE. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:15 PM ON DECEMBER 11,1992, A REACTION OCCURRED WHILE LOADING SODIUM BROMATE INTO A SPEC 57 TOTE TANKMOUNTED ON A TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT. THE TANK (WHICH WAS THOUGHT TO BE EMPTY) HADPREVIOUSLY HELD 30% AQUEOUS SODIUM THIOSULFATE, OF WHICH IT IS ESTIMATED THAT10 GALLONS REMAINED. THE TANK WAS LOADED WITH 214 GALLONS OF WATER PRIOR TO THEADDITION OF 214 POUNDS OF SODIUM BROMATE. THE TEMPERATURE OF THE TANK ROSERAPIDLY AND A BROWNISH VAPOR CLOUD WAS RELEASED. A CHEMICAL REACTION ISBELIEVED TO HAVE OCCURRED BETWEEN THE BROMATE AND THIOSULFATE WHICH IS EXPECTEDTO GENERATE BROMINE OXIDES AND SULFUR DIOXIDE (CAS#7446-09-5) THE DSI IN-HOUSEEMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS PUT INOT ACTION AND THE DSI TULSA EMERGENCYRESPONSE GROUP CONTACTED THE NRC. THE LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT (LOCALHAZMAT) RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY. THE POLICE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED THE ADJACENTPROPERTY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SPRAYED WATER ON THE TANK TO REDUCE THETEMPERATURE. THE CHEMICAL REACTION WAS QUENCHED BY TRANSFERRIN THE MATERIAL TOA BATCH MIXER WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED WITH 50 BARRELS OF WATER. THE DURATION OFTHE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATLEY 3 HOURS AND 20 MINUTES. THREE PEOPLE (EMPLOYEESOF SCHNEIDER SPECIALIZED CARRIERS, WHICH IS NEXT TO OUR FACILITY) WENT TO THEHOSPITAL AFTER INHALING THE VAPOR, BUT LEFT THE EMERGENCY ROOM BEFORE THEY WEREEXAMINED. THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NSR (CASE#148796) AND THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION (TWC) TEXAS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER(TERC).
